Residual Error

The top 5 models based on RMSE have the following model_id’s

## [1] 916 972 704 388 369

Look at residual error distribution for 10 models. The errors from the 10 models will be used as a proxy for the 1920 models in the dataset. Look at the top 5 models based on RMSE rank and 5 randomly selected models from the top 100 based on RMSE.

Check residual error distribution

Check distribution of residuals for each model

qplot(residuals, data = data,facets=model_id~.,binwidth=2) 

qplot(residuals, data = data,facets=model_id~.,geom="density")

Check distribution of residuals for each model_id and day combination. Rows are separate models and columns are days

qplot(residuals, data = data,facets=model_id~doy,binwidth=2, xlab="day") 

qplot(residuals, data = data,facets=model_id~doy,geom="density", xlab="day")

The distributions seem to take the shape of a normal distribution, although not perfect.

Check residuals vs observed for each model. The residuals are not distributed randomly around the 0 line.

qplot(yield,residuals,data=data, facets=model_id~.) + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color="red")

Check residuals vs observed for each model/day combination. The residuals are not distributed randomly around the 0 line.

qplot(yield,residuals,data=data,facets=model_id~doy) + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color="red")

Check Q-Q plot for each model.

Check Q-Q plot for each model/day combination.

# calculate Quanitiles for qqline for model and day
df2 <- ddply(.data = data, .variables = .(model_id,doy), function(dat){
             q <- qqnorm(dat$residuals, plot = FALSE)
             dat$xq <- q$x
             dat
}
)
#Q-Q plot for each model
ggplot(data = df2, aes(x = xq, y = residuals)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  xlab("Theoretical") +
  ylab("Sample") +
  facet_grid(model_id~doy)
